        // How I Got Here Section
        .card.shadow-sm.mb-5
          .card-body.p-4
            .d-flex.align-items-center.mb-3
              .bg-info.rounded-circle.p-2.me-3
                i.bi.bi-lightbulb.text-white
              h3.mb-0.text-info How I Ended Up on This Mountain
            p.mb-3 This whole thing started with some conversations I've been having with colleagues about how AI is changing the way we learn and work. We kept coming back to these psychological patterns that everyone seems to recognize but struggles to articulate.

            p.mb-3 You know the Dunning-Kruger effect, right? That thing where people who know very little are super confident, while actual experts are more humble about what they know. We'd all seen this play out in our careers‚Äîthe junior developer who thinks they can architect the entire system after reading one blog post, or the manager who becomes an "AI expert" after a weekend with ChatGPT.

            p.mb-3 But then someone brought up imposter syndrome, and things got interesting. Here you have the opposite problem‚Äîcompetent people who feel like frauds, constantly worried they'll be "found out" for not knowing enough. We realized we were seeing both phenomena in the same teams, sometimes in the same people at different times.

            p.mb-3 The more we talked about it, the more I started wondering: what happens when you throw AI into this mix? These tools are incredibly good at making you feel knowledgeable. They give you these confident, well-structured responses that can make anyone sound like an expert in casual conversation.

            p.mb-3 I started thinking about my own experience. How many times had I asked an AI about something, gotten a great-sounding answer, and walked away feeling like I "got it"? How often was I actually just fooling myself?

            p.mb-0 That's when I realized we needed a better way to think about this whole journey. The traditional Dunning-Kruger curve didn't quite capture what AI was doing to our learning process. And imposter syndrome felt like it was happening at the wrong times for the wrong reasons.

            .alert.alert-primary.mt-3
              .d-flex.align-items-start
                i.bi.bi-info-circle.me-2.mt-1
                div
                  p.mb-0 So I started sketching out this mountain metaphor, trying to reconcile these different patterns I was seeing. What if the learning journey wasn't just about going from ignorant confidence to informed humility? What if AI was creating these new phases‚Äîextended periods of false confidence, deeper crashes, and different kinds of self-doubt?

            p.mt-3.mb-0 The Mountain of Misunderstanding isn't just about the Dunning-Kruger effect. It's about how AI tools are reshaping our entire relationship with knowledge and confidence, creating new peaks and valleys that we need to learn to navigate.

